Description: Fix CVE-2025-69224 - Reject non-ascii characters in some headers
 The pure-Python HTTP parser uses .lower() without an isascii() guard on
 Content-Encoding and Transfer-Encoding header values. Non-ASCII characters
 whose case-fold maps to ASCII control keywords (e.g., U+212A KELVIN SIGN
 -> 'k', ligatures U+FB06/U+FB02 -> 'st'/'fl') smuggle past the comparison.
 A proxy that compares case-sensitively will disagree with aiohttp on
 framing/encoding, enabling HTTP request smuggling.
 .
 Backported from upstream commit 32677f2adfd907420c078dda6b79225c6f4ebce0
 (cherry-pick of 5affd64). Adapted to aiohttp 3.8.6:
 - Inlined isascii() guard around existing CONTENT_ENCODING enc.lower()
   check (target lacks _is_supported_upgrade helper and zstd encoding).
 - Inlined isascii() guard around existing Transfer-Encoding chunked
   comparison (target lacks _is_chunked_te helper).
 - Same isascii() guard added to the Cython parser CONTENT_ENCODING check.
 - Upgrade header hunks omitted: target's pyx uses cparser.upgrade flag
   (llhttp-derived, not vulnerable) and the pure-Python parser does not
   inspect the Upgrade header value (only Connection: upgrade).
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/commit/32677f2adfd907420c078dda6b79225c6f4ebce0
